            <h2>Understanding Body Mass Index (BMI)</h2>
            <p>
                Body Mass Index (BMI) is a widely used metric for assessing whether an individual has a healthy body weight for a given height. Developed by mathematician Adolphe Quetelet in the 19th century, BMI has become a standard tool in both clinical and public health settings to categorize individuals into different weight statuses: underweight, normal weight, overweight, and obese.
            </p>
            <p>
                While BMI is a valuable indicator, it's essential to understand its scope, limitations, and the factors it considers. This comprehensive guide delves into the intricacies of BMI, providing you with the knowledge to interpret your BMI results accurately and understand their implications for your health.
            </p>
            
            <h3>How is BMI Calculated?</h3>
            <p>
                BMI is calculated using a simple mathematical formula that relates your weight to your height. The formula differs slightly based on the unit system you use:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Metric System (kg/m²):</strong> <em>BMI = Weight (kg) / (Height (m))²</em></li>
                <li><strong>Imperial System (lbs/in²):</strong> <em>BMI = (Weight (lbs) / (Height (in))²) × 703</em></li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                This calculation provides a single numerical value that places you within a weight category, facilitating quick assessments and comparisons.
            </p>
            
            <h3>Understanding BMI Categories</h3>
            <p>
                BMI categories help in identifying potential health risks associated with different weight statuses. Here's a breakdown of the standard BMI categories:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Underweight:</strong> BMI less than 18.5</li>
                <li><strong>Normal weight:</strong> BMI between 18.5 and 24.9</li>
                <li><strong>Overweight:</strong> BMI between 25 and 29.9</li>
                <li><strong>Obese:</strong> BMI of 30 or higher</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                These categories serve as general guidelines. However, individual health can vary based on numerous factors, including muscle mass, bone density, age, and gender.
            </p>
            
            <h3>Factors Affecting BMI Accuracy</h3>
            <p>
                While BMI is a useful screening tool, several factors can influence its accuracy:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Muscle Mass:</strong> Individuals with high muscle mass may have a higher BMI, classifying them as overweight or obese, even if their body fat percentage is low.</li>
                <li><strong>Bone Density:</strong> People with denser bones may have higher BMIs without excess body fat.</li>
                <li><strong>Age:</strong> As people age, muscle mass tends to decrease, potentially altering BMI classifications.</li>
                <li><strong>Gender:</strong> Men and women typically have different body compositions, which can affect BMI interpretations.</li>
                <li><strong>Body Frame Size:</strong> Individuals with larger frames may naturally weigh more, influencing their BMI.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                Recognizing these factors is crucial for interpreting BMI results accurately and avoiding misconceptions about one's health status.
            </p>
            
