            <h4>BMI for Children and Teens</h4>
            <p>
                For individuals under 18, BMI is interpreted differently. Children's BMI is age and gender-specific, as children are growing and their body compositions are changing. Instead of fixed categories, BMI percentiles are used:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Underweight:</strong> Less than the 5th percentile</li>
                <li><strong>Healthy weight:</strong> 5th percentile to less than the 85th percentile</li>
                <li><strong>Overweight:</strong> 85th percentile to less than the 95th percentile</li>
                <li><strong>Obese:</strong> 95th percentile or higher</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                These percentiles are based on growth charts developed by health organizations like the CDC and WHO.
            </p>
            
            <h4>BMI for Athletes</h4>
